{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.16,0.26,0.18,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77560"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"2919"},{"type":"tags","id":"3620"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6429"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77560"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with one month of ankle swelling. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 165/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has bilateral pitting ankle oedema. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 120 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (35-50)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrinary protein/creatinine ratio: 280 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;30)\u003Cbr /\u003EDysmorphic red cells seen on urine microscopy\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA renal biopsy shows membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis with subendothelial and mesangial immune deposits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following liver conditions is most commonly associated with this renal diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune hepatitis","Primary biliary cholangitis","Hepatitis C","Hepatitis B","Alcohol-related liver disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with proteinuria, microscopic haematuria, hypertension and mild renal impairment, and has been found to have membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis (MPGN) on renal biopsy. MPGN can be primary (idiopathic) or secondary to various conditions, with chronic infections being a major cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C\u003C/strong\u003E infection is the most common cause of secondary MPGN in adults. The association is thought to be due to the deposition of circulating immune complexes containing hepatitis C antigens. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary biliary cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with various forms of glomerulonephritis, but MPGN is not typically associated with this condition. The most common renal manifestation of PBC is tubulointerstitial nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol-related liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with MPGN. While it can cause various renal complications, these are usually related to cirrhosis and portal hypertension rather than immune complex deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E infection can cause various forms of glomerulonephritis, but membranous nephropathy is more commonly associated with hepatitis B than MPGN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with various forms of glomerulonephritis, but MPGN is not a typical manifestation. IgA nephropathy is more commonly seen in autoimmune hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of MPGN should prompt investigation for underlying causes, particularly hepatitis C. Other conditions associated with MPGN include chronic bacterial infections (such as endocarditis), autoimmune diseases (such as systemic lupus erythematosus), and monoclonal gammopathies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis (MPGN) is commonly associated with chronic hepatitis C infection."],"references":["Habas Sr E, Farfar K, Errayes N, et al. Hepatitis Virus C-associated Nephropathy: A Review and Update. Cureus. 2022 Jul 27;14(7):e27322"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T14:14:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T14:15:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77560"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07